{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_inkster_ver01/data/sn88063294/00340589075/1945081801/0510.xml":{"full_text":"MAMIMIIA I Jl 1 m MW\nB I B B B A MR B A -A I w v A b B\nI;K b By B'M W -m lAb V IM B\nH\nMayor Gives\n119,000,000\nWork Plan\nMayor Jeffries today sub-\nTnitted to common council a\n$19,000,000 civic expansion\nprogram which would provide\nwork for thousands of per\nsons during the six to nine\nmonths it takes to reconvert\nthe auto industry to com\nplete peacetime production.\nIn letter to council, Jeffries\nrecommended tfc-at nnrf than\n11.000.000 be spent as soon as\npossible on the Douglas and Jef\nfries housing projects and the\nbalance of the money he ex\npended on recreation renters,\nschools, traffic signal extensions,\nSewers and Wltet ID\nThe letter, the contents of\nwhich were heard today by only\nCounnlmen Sweeny and Lodge,\nsaid, in part:\n\u201cIt Is believed that at |ea*t\nalx to nine months will be ron\naumed before the automobile\nIndustry ia completely recon\nverted, during which Interim the\nunemployed will he augmented\nby thousands of discharged serv\nicemen whose only remaining\nfear la inaecurlty.\n\u2022\u2018The end of the war caught\nthe city napping. But our ad\nvanced planning la at the point\nwhere we could ask for bids\non the projects mentioned\nwithin SO day a.\u201d\nDepartment of Public Works\nCommissioner Dlenn C. Richards\nWill present further details to\ncouncil Monday\nAuto Makers\nFace Big Task\nThe immense task of reconvert\ning the automobile industry and\nthe urgency for speed to combat\nunemployment are equalled only\nby the task the motor industry\ncompleted successfully after Pearl\nHarbor, general manager George\nRomney Of the Automobile Man\nufacturers\u2019 Association said today.\nMore than 700 prime contracts\nIn the Detroit area have been\ncanceled by the Air Technical\nService Command, while the AAF\nvoided contracts for 31.000 air\nplanes and other orders at an\nestimated savings of $9,000,000-\n000.\nREINSTATE CONTRACT\nThe government loday had re\ninstated its contract with the\nFord Motor Co. for production of\ntank engines at the Lincoln Plant\nWorkers have been ordered to\nreturn Monday. The tank eon\ntract had been canceled, together\nwith AAF orders for Pratt and\nWhitney aircraft engines\nRomney said it was \u201cunfortun\nate\u201d that the government did not\nanticipate the sudden end of the\nwar and authorize preliminary\nreconversion work.\nON V-E PROGRAM\n\u201cAs a result, the Industry Is\njust embarking on a partial\nproduction program, which was\nauthorized after V-E Day,**\nRomney explained.\n\u201cIt appears now that the\ngreatest unemployment will he\nduring the next three months.\nIta extent cannot he predicted\nat this time. The number of\njobs opened should be on the\nIncrease hy October, and should\nmount quite rapidly until, hy\nnert spring, employment should\nsurpass anything ever seen In\npeacetime.\u201d\nEXTRA\nMissing Baby Returned\nTHE WATSON BABY SAFE AT HOME\nI if m JL^mMi^^HBBBBBBBIB\nm iW\nf i it\nah v Tie M\n\nmy\n\n4 v ~'N^dH^BlVr\n\u25a0p- T\ni\u00dfwyir n\ni v V\u25a0 iB.- jgfc.\nV /\\a f\ni\nL I :frks-f\nr Wk\nv. Lipins\nM x Hr Jl\n2r\nThree-year-old Miriam Pauline Watson\nsleeping blissfully today in her mother\u2019s\napartment at 695 Brainard after she was\nTriplets* Chances\nTo Survive Good\nThree tiny girls who just fit into the hollow' made by a man\u2019s\ncupped hands will survive, authorities at the Northwestern branch\nof Grace Hospital, where they were born yesterday to the wife\nof a General Motors analyst, said today.\nThe triplets, who toge\u00bbher\nweighed only b pounds 124 ounces,\nare doing splendidly, a hospital\nspokesman said, and there is every\nrhanee that they will continue to\nprogress unless there should be\nunforeseen complications.\nNurses said the birth of the\ntriplets, first to arrive in Detroit\nsince the war\u2019s end. amazed and\ndelighted the mother, Mrs. Mark\n.Johnstone of 1530 Seward.\n\u201cMy goodness,\u201d sne told an\nattendant who brought her the\nnews. \u201cI can\u2019t go,on having an\nunbalanced family like this for\nlong. I\u2019ll Just have to have a\nlittle hoy.\u201d\nMrs Johnstone is 35 years old,\nand has been married about eight\nyears. The Triplets are hpr first\nchildren. They were delivered a\nmonth prematurely.\nThe girls, known as yet only as\nA. R and C in the order of their\narrival by Caesarean operation,\nare being kept in two incubators.\nThey are being fed a special for\nmula. a drop at a time, through\nan eye-dropper.\nThey weight 2 pounds 2 ounces.\n12 pounds 3 ounces and 2 pounds\n74 ounces. The tw-o smaller girls\nshare one incubator, their \"big\nsister\u201d has one all to herself.\nEach is fed a special formula,\naecording to her weight, every\nj two hours. They receive water,\n'also by the eye-dropper method.\nI \u201cbetween meals.\u201d About a quar\nter of an ounce constitutes each\nI \"meal.\u201d\nNormal babies receive nourish\nment every four hours.\nThe girls arrived at 9 a. nr. 9:01\na. m and 9:03 a. m. yesterday. So\nfragile did they appear that phy\nisicians clapped them into the in\ncubators after weighing, without\nstopping to take other measure\nments.\nDETRWPiiPTO/IES\nOnly Detroit Newspaper Carrying Both A~ \u2014lnternational News Service and United Press\nsstm TF.AK,\nho. 11l\nC Detroit 31, Mich., Saturday, Aug. 18,1945\nTime* Photo\nreturned from Chicago by Mrs. Jackie\nReynolds, who was charged with kidnap\ning her and is now being held by police.\nActor Bows to Heiress\nHOLLYWOOD. Aug. 17 (UP)\nCary Grant, third husband of\nRarbara Hutton, who faces her\ndivorce suit in superior court,\nAug. 30. will not contest the ac\ntion, he indicated today.\nTHE WEATHER\nHOI ItLT TKMPF.RVTI RES\n12 mid M s m 10 m. *T\n1 m 6 2 flaw 54 11am 7 J\n2am 07 7am 57 12 noon ~i\n3am 50 i in. M 1 p m. 70\nSam 63 9\u00abm 60\nThe aun will aet at t ,10 p m today and\nrla* tomorrow at 6 42 a m\nTh* moon will rl\u00bb* at 4 04 p m today\nand set tomorrow at 1 30 a m\nm\n\\t*\\ i.\nToday\u2019s pollen rount Is 83.\nATTENTION, GRAHAM PaIOE second ahtft\nemploy*** Du* to contract cancellation* only\nemployee* !n powerhoua*. maintenance de\npartment and tank department ahould report\nfor work thli afternoon. AH other employee*\nshould report to employment emce for clear\nance atxt wees \u2014A4*.\nNurse Jailed;\nMother Faces\nCourt Action\n\nUnharmed, three-year-old\nMiriam Pauline Watson was\nreturned from Chicago today\nwhile both her mother and\nher alleged abductor face\ncourt charges.\nMiriam was returnW to her\nhome at 695 Bramard by her\nnursemaid, 30-year-old Mrs. Alva\n\"Jackie\u201d Reynolds, who. according\nto Detective Sgt. Lee C. Reming\nton, will be charged with kidnap\ning.\nPolicewoman Eleanor C. Hutzel\nsaid a warrant will be asked in\njuvenile court charging the\nmother, Mm. Luella Watson, with\nneglect of the pretty, blonde, blue\neyed child who disappeared Tues\nday night at the height of the vic\ntory celebration.\nFATHER KEEPS RIGHTS\nMiss Hutzel pointed out, how\never, that the warrant against the\nmother does not jeopardize the\nright of the father, Pvt. Lyndon\nWatson, to have the child when he\nreturns from service.\nMrs. Reynolds, who was taken\ninto custody shortly after her ar\nrival from Chicago at 2 a. m., was\nindignant at her arrest.\n\"This U aU silly,\u201d she said.\n\u201cMrs. Watson told me she didn\u2019t\nlike the child.!*\n\u201cShe said I could have her.\nShe said Miriam was a burden\nand kept her from being able to\nrun around.\nKEPT HOME AND BABY\n\u201cI took Mariam to Chicago\nwith the Intention of scaring\nher mother and making her\nrealize that Miriam is a fine I\nchild.\n\u201cMrs. Watson often neglected\nMiriam.\n\"I\u2019ve had complete charge of\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 5)\n2<l\nInto Argentina Port\nBI\u2019ENOS AIRES. Aug. 17 (UP)\n\u2014Another German submarine\u2014'\nthe U-977\u2014with 45 officers and\nmen aboard, entered Mar del,\nPlata at 10:45 a m.\u2014three months\nand one week after the Nazi sur\nrender.\nThe first Nazi sub to enter\nBuenos Aires for surrender, turned\nup more than a mbnth ago.\nThe sub was escorted into har\nbor by two Argentine submarines\nand an Argentine naval plane.\nIt was believed to be one of\ntwo subs reported off the Argen\ntine coast about a week after\nthe U-530 gave up.\nIt was presumed that the prece\ndent established by the U-530 sur\nrender would be followed and\nthat the submarine and crew\n\"It\u2019s ptacs or\npioets\u2014sign\nquick, Hlrohlto!\"\nFORECAST:\nClear tonight,\npartly cloudy\nand warmer\ntomorrow.\nA. M Cl Ma I\nSub Sails\n5 Cents\nArnold Reveals Things to Come I\nHuge Superbomber\nNew 11. S. Weapon\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 17 (INS)\u2014Gen H. H. Arnold\ndisclosed today that the United States has developed a gi\ngantic superbomber, greater than the B-29, with a range of\nmore than 5.000 miles to insure peace in the postwar world.\nArnold, commanding general of the army air forces, made\nthe disclosure at a special news conference.\nThe general also promised that Tokyo would be used as a\ndefensive base and that fantastic new weapons of a \u201cBuck Rogers\nPetain Gets\nLife Term\nLONDON, Aug. 17\u2014(UP)\u2014\nRadio Paris, heard by BBC, re\nported today that the death sen\ntence of Marshal Henri Philippe\nPetain has been commuted by\nGen. Charles De Gaulle to life im\nprisonment.\nThe announcement said: \"De\nGaulle has commuted the death\nsentence imposed on Petain to\nlife imprisonment.\u201d\nNewsprint Increase\nFrom Canada Seen\nTORONTO. Aug. 17 (UP)\nThe Toronto Financial Post will\nsay tomorrow that Canadian pa\nper mills may bv* able to make\na \u2018modest\u201d increase in shipments\nof newsprint to the United States\nMany Killed in Oslo Blast\nLONDON. Aug. 17 (INS)\u2014The\ncity of Oslo was rocked today and\na large number of persons killed\nand injured when an ammunition\nstore in the dock area blew up.\nw'ould he fumed over to the\nUnited Nations. The U-530 is\nstill here under repairs and a\nU. S prize crew is waiting to\ntake it to the United States.\nIn the Times TODAY\nr\u00bb*\u00ab\nBettor Rnlth\n\u2022\u25a0Bara\u201d lUrr\n(\u2022min 20. 21\nCraw w#r4 rattle 20\nDlinn 0\nDarling O\nMitorlal r>i\u00ab 0\nr.\u00ab- O\nrlnurUl 1 7\nttaUo'a r>rtw* 20\nH\u00abn\u00bbr RnU 10\nHormrapt O\nMilton 0\nMary Hawnrth O\nMovie Fragrant 10\nPi I torn O\nRati\nFetler 0\n*MI\u00bb Pmfrimi 20\nRitlan Chart O\nBlplry 21\nRany\u00abn O\nSociety 0\nSpnru 14. IB\nStar*. Nrrm 14\nVeteran*' Irrrln O\nWant 44a 18. 1*\nW Inrhrll\nW ltMn| Writ 20\nWhat* IM\nAn\u00abwer* a 0\nWomen Par* 4\nD*. J. C. TOOLE. DEMIST\nlie W Lafayatte, at Michigan, opp City\nHall. Houra. \u00bb9. TaL CA SAM Adv.\nRED\nLINE\nvariety\u201d were being developed.\nSTRESSES RESEARCH\nArnold also revealed that he\nplanned soon to step out as chief\nof the army air forces although\nhe declined to give a specific date.\nThe general stressed the im\nportance of American research to\ndevelop weapons so fantastic and\nterrible that aggressors would\nfear to start another conflict.\nArnold refused to discuss in de\ntail the powerful new bombs and\nwould not compare it to the B-29\nor the B-32 except in vague terms.\n\u201cWe have a plane today com\ning along which Is considerably\nbetter than the B-29 and has\nbetter than a 5.000-mlle range,\u201d\nArnold said.\nNEW BUZZ BOMBS\nHe added that America also Is\ndeveloping new types of buzz\nbombs and rocket weapons which\nhave explosive heads that will\nmake them explode on reaction\nto heat, light and metal.\nArnold foresaw the day when\nlong-range bombers with jet pro\npulsion would fly without crews\nvast distances to drop missiles on\nenemy targets.\nHe Indicated that the United\nStates now is working on weapons\nwhich will he attracted by steel,\nlight and heat so that they will\nexplode when they come in con\ntact.\n\"When you think of our pres\nent long-range airplane and the\natomic bomb you get a Burk\nRogers conception of war w hich\nIs right on our threshold,\"\nArnold added.\nMAPS ISLAND RASES\nHe continued, however, that the\nUnited States must keep present\nproven weapon? until the new ones!\nare being produced in quantity'\nand their complete effectiveness\nhas been tried.\nIn adition to bases in the Tokyo\narea. Arnold said that the United,\nStates also must control the fol\nlowing stepping stones to insure\npeace in the Pacific:\nSan Francisco, Honolulu, Mid\nway, Wake, Marcus and Truk.\nTO ALL FORD EMPLOYEES! The Port Motor\nCompany plana to r*\u00bbum* operation* Monday\nPrincipal eiceptlon will be in the case of work\ner* who were employed on the Pratt and\nWhitney aircraft engine contract which hai\nbeen canceled by the United State* Govern-}\nment. All worker* entitled to vacation* on\nthl* Job are to take their vacation* at thta\ntime, and will be notified by pottcard aa to i\nwhen they thould report for work\nOpen hearth and aoaktng pi** will return*\noperation* on the Mo 3 Shift Sunday\nRolling milt worker a on the 4 4-inch 32- 1\nInch and l*-lnch mill* will return* wntg re,\nthe Vo 1 Shift Monday All other mill* will\nreturn* operation! on th* No 3 Shift Monday I\nFORD MOTOR COMPANY Adv 1\nGen. Arnold\nLists Isles\nTo Be Held\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 17\n(INS)\u2014 Gen. H. H. Arnold,\ncommander of the Army Air\nForces, disclosed today that\nthe United States will use\nTokyo as a defensive base to\ninsure future peace in the\nFar East.\nArnold asserted at a special\nnew* conference that in lion\n\u2022to bases in the Tokyo aieu, this\ncountry also must control the\nfollowing stepping stones in the\nj Pacific:\nSan Francisco, Honolulu. Mid\nway, Wake, Marcus and Truk.\nThis was the first mention by a\nhigh official that the Jap-held\nAmerican island of Wake and the\nenemy islands of Marcus and\nTruk, as well as Tokyo, would\nhe used as bases to maintain\npeace.\nNEW YORK, Aug. 17\n(INS)\u2014Robert Shaplen.N\u00dfC\nand Newsweek correspondent,\nreported from Manila today\nthat U. S. planes on a routine\nphoto reconnaissance flight\nover Tokyo at noon today\n(Manila time) were attacked\nby Jap fighting planes and\nanti-aircraft\nShaplen said four of the newest\ntype Superbombers, B-32, were at\ntacked by eight or 10 Japanese\nfighters and driven into the mid\ndle of a terrific anti-aircraft bar\nrage.\nOne of the planes flying at\n20.000 feet was badly hit on the\nwing flaps and tail by about 50\nack ack bursts and it returned to\nthe Philippines full of holes.\nPilots told Shaplen they were\ngreatly surprised when attacked\nby the Jap fighters. They added,\nhowever, that the fighters were\nnot \u201ctoo\u201d aggressive.\nThe B-32 gunners said they shot\ndown two of the Nip fighters.\n\u2018Quit YouT Stalling,\u2019\nMacArthur Warns\n1 MANILA, Aug. 17 (UP)\u2014Gen.\nMacArthur ordered Japan today\nto stop stalling and to send sur\nrender emissaries to his head\nquarters in Manila \"without\nfurther delay.\"\n(An INS dispatch from Wash\nington suggested that Japan's\ndelaying tactics Indicated that\nthe Japanese government was\nstalling for time to ease the\ni \u201chock on the people of Amerl\n-1 can entry into their \"sacred\u201d\nIsland. Gen. Somervell, com\nmander of the army service\nforces, announced, however, that\nAmerican troops would land In\nJapan \u201cfully prepared\u201d for com\nbat. If need be. He confirmed\nreports that Gen. MacArthur\nIntended to overlook no possibil\nity of Japanese treachery. An\nother dispatch Indicated that\nMacArthur also Intends to force\nthe Japanese to sign the sur\nrender terms In Emperor Hlro\nhlto\u2019s own palace.)\nPlainly irritated over Japnnes*\nbickering. MacArthur brushed\naside Tokyo\u2019s request for clarifi\ncation of the duties of the Manila\nmission with this brusque order\nto imperial general headquarters:\n\"Your assumption that sign\ning of the surrender terms Is\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 2)\nStarlifM Daaetng Al for Ml* a Or chert/a G 4.\nRiver-GrevnScM A4a 5V oitaty tan Saw\nA4*.","height":"27894","width":"21468"}}
